  "answer": "Both texts are in the corpus and can be read directly. Iqbal's 'Wataniyat' is Bang-e-Dara Part 3, chapter 25 (allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8, ch. 25). Charles Comte's Traité de Législation Vol II is charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-ii-20331d.\n\nIqbal's argument in 'Wataniyat': territorial nationalism is the greatest of the new age's idols — 'The robe it wears is Faith's own final desecration.' He insists that in the discourse of the state the Nation is merely land, whereas in the Prophet's teaching the Homeland is by God's command. Nationalism sows rivalry, enables conquest, and tears apart both God's creation and Islamic brotherhood. The proper collective identity is the trans-territorial umma.\n\nComte's approach in Traité de Législation Vol II (especially chs. 3 and 13): collective identity is grounded empirically — in the observable 'espèces ou variétés' of humanity (Caucasian, Mongolian, Ethiopian, American, Malay), each with characteristic physical and moral traits shaped by climate, terrain, and means of subsistence. Ch. 13 argues that the identity between the laws of a nation and the morals that constitute it is so real that writers on barbarous peoples never distinguished the one from the other. Collective identity, for Comte, is a natural, material phenomenon readable from customs, laws, and environmental conditions.\n\nWhere a productive disagreement can be staged:\n\n1. Basis of legitimate collective identity: Iqbal says collective identity must be divinely commanded — only the umma has legitimate grounds. Comte says collective identity is empirically constituted by shared physical characteristics, climate, and moral-legal customs. Both actually reject simple territorial nationalism (Iqbal because it replaces God with an idol; Comte because his categories are racial/environmental, not merely geographic), but their positive replacements clash sharply: revealed universal community vs. naturally differentiated particular peoples.\n\n2. Universalism vs. natural pluralism: Iqbal's universalism demands that the lines between peoples be erased in favor of one brotherhood under God. Comte's framework accepts a plurality of distinct peoples as natural and studies how each develops its own legal-moral order from material conditions — implying no single community should subsume all others.\n\n3. Power and domination: Iqbal charges that nationalism enables conquest and brings the weak man's home to its knees. Comte's naturalistic account of peoples, grounded in racial and environmental differences, risks treating power differentials between peoples as natural consequences of their constitutions — precisely the move Iqbal's critique targets as ideological cover for imperial domination.\n\n4. Role of revelation: Iqbal's entire argument rests on divine command as the only legitimate ground for community. Comte's positivist-empiricist method leaves no epistemic role for revelation — collective identity is explained entirely through observable material causes. This is the deepest fault line: whether collective identity has a transcendent warrant or only a natural-historical one.",
