**Summary of findings:** 'Wataniyat' is Bang-e-Dara Part 3, ch. 25. Iqbal calls the nation the greatest of modernity's new idols — nationalism is merely "land" in political discourse, whereas the true homeland is divinely commanded (the umma). Comte's Vol II grounds collective identity entirely in empirically observed physical "espèces" (races), climate, and material conditions, with ch. 13 arguing that a people's laws and morals are essentially identical — both arising from natural causes.

The productive disagreements are: (1) **basis of collective identity** — divine command vs. natural-material constitution; (2) **universalism vs. natural pluralism** — Iqbal wants one brotherhood dissolving national lines, Comte accepts a plurality of naturally differentiated peoples; (3) **power and conquest** — Iqbal charges nationalism enables domination of the weak; Comte's naturalism risks treating power differentials as natural consequences of racial/environmental differences; (4) **the role of revelation** — the deepest fault line, since Comte's positivist method admits no transcendent warrant for community at all.
